Posterior border of the propodosoma without protuberances. In front of the bothridium, at each side, at first a round, light spot, then an area of smaller irregular spots. A similar, unpaired group occurs just between the bothridia. Medially and anally of the bothridia at each side a single light spot, posteriorly of which the chitin is slightly thickened, without, however, forming a protuberance as in related species. The disposition of the propodosomatal hairs is shown in figs. 5a, 6a. The sensillus (length about 120 
y
) is flagelliform; it is directed obliquely backward. The interlamellar hairs (length about 80 
y
) are also directed obliquely backward; they stand close to the bothridia. Bothridium cup-shaped. Exobothridial hairs close to the antiaxial side of the bothridia; they are strongly curved, and are directed frontward and upward.

On femur I dorsally a strong, serrate hair that is curved to the front close above the base. On leg IV similar hairs on trochanter, femur, and genu. The remaining hairs of the legs partly with similar expansions as the notogastral hairs. Solenidion of tibia IV free, and strongly curved in the middle. The length (in 
